46. GROUP BY
Definition

The GROUP BY clause groups rows that have the same values in specified columns.

It is commonly used with aggregate functions like:

COUNT()
SUM()
AVG()
MIN()
MAX()
Syntax
SELECT column_name,
       aggregate_function(column_name)
FROM table_name
GROUP BY column_name;
Example
Employee Table
Name	Department	Salary
Rahul	IT	40000
Priya	HR	50000
Aman	IT	30000
SELECT Department,
SUM(Salary)
FROM Employee
GROUP BY Department;

Output

Department	SUM(Salary)
IT	70000
HR	50000
47. HAVING
Definition

The HAVING clause filters groups created by GROUP BY.

Unlike WHERE, it can filter based on aggregate functions.

Syntax
SELECT column_name,
aggregate_function(column_name)
FROM table_name
GROUP BY column_name
HAVING condition;
Example
SELECT Department,
AVG(Salary)
FROM Employee
GROUP BY Department
HAVING AVG(Salary) > 35000;

Output

Department	AVG(Salary)
HR	50000
48. Difference Between WHERE and HAVING
WHERE	HAVING
Filters individual rows	Filters grouped records
Executed before GROUP BY	Executed after GROUP BY
Cannot use aggregate functions directly	Can use aggregate functions
Used with SELECT, UPDATE, DELETE	Used mainly with GROUP BY
Example
WHERE
SELECT *
FROM Employee
WHERE Salary > 40000;

Filters rows before grouping.

HAVING
SELECT Department,
COUNT(*)
FROM Employee
GROUP BY Department
HAVING COUNT(*) > 1;

Filters groups after grouping.

49. Aggregate vs Scalar Functions
Definition
Aggregate Functions

Operate on multiple rows and return one result.

Examples:

COUNT()
SUM()
AVG()
MIN()
MAX()
Scalar Functions

Operate on a single value and return one value for each row.

Examples:

UPPER()
LOWER()
LENGTH()
ROUND()
NOW()
Comparison
Aggregate Functions	Scalar Functions
Work on multiple rows	Work on one value
Return one result per group/query	Return one result per row
Often used with GROUP BY	Used in any query
Examples: SUM(), COUNT()	Examples: UPPER(), LOWER()
Example
Aggregate Function
SELECT AVG(Salary)
FROM Employee;

Output

AVG(Salary)
40000
Scalar Function
SELECT UPPER(Name)
FROM Employee;

Output

UPPER(Name)
RAHUL
PRIYA
AMAN
50. ROLLUP / CUBE (Conceptual)
Definition
ROLLUP

ROLLUP generates subtotals and a grand total for grouped data.

It creates hierarchical summaries from left to right.

Syntax
SELECT column1,
column2,
SUM(column3)
FROM table_name
GROUP BY ROLLUP(column1, column2);
Example
Sales Table
Department	Month	Sales
IT	Jan	10000
IT	Feb	12000
HR	Jan	8000
SELECT Department,
Month,
SUM(Sales)
FROM Sales
GROUP BY ROLLUP(Department, Month);

Output (Conceptual)

Department	Month	Sales
IT	Jan	10000
IT	Feb	12000
IT	NULL	22000
HR	Jan	8000
HR	NULL	8000
NULL	NULL	30000
Definition
CUBE

CUBE generates all possible combinations of subtotals, including row-wise, column-wise, and grand totals.

It is more comprehensive than ROLLUP.

Syntax
SELECT column1,
column2,
SUM(column3)
FROM table_name
GROUP BY CUBE(column1, column2);
Example
SELECT Department,
Month,
SUM(Sales)
FROM Sales
GROUP BY CUBE(Department, Month);

This returns:

Sales by Department and Month
Sales by Department
Sales by Month
Grand Total
Difference Between ROLLUP and CUBE
ROLLUP	CUBE
Produces hierarchical subtotals	Produces all possible subtotals
Includes grand total	Includes grand total
Fewer summary rows	More summary rows
Best for hierarchical reports	Best for multidimensional analysis
Quick Interview Revision
Question	One-Line Answer
